{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00529040106/1930110901/0001.xml":{"full_text":"Weather\nARIZONA: Fair Sunday and Mon\nday, little change in temperature.\nDOUGLAS^ maximum tem\nperature yed here yesterday\nwas 70 dea and the minimum\nwas 41 degr t.*\nVOL. XXV.\nNational Parties United In Seeking Prosperity\nLegion Of\nCity\u2019s Needy\nSeeks Work\nChicago\u2019s 300,000 Register\nin Public Schools for\nState Aid\nMany Are Desperate\nAnd All Ask For Jobs\nEvery Age and Many\nWalks of Life Repre\nsented Among Throng\nCHICAGO, Nov. 8 UPy\u2014Chi\ncago's legion of unemployed\u2014a\nwas section of artistic pro\nfessional and industrial life\nmarched 300,000 rtnng into 350\npublic schools today and regis\ntered their needs that governor\nEmerson's unemployment com\nmission might work out their re\nlief.\nDesperate were the needs of\nmany for food, for rent money,\nbut to the last man and wc\nman they wanted work\u2014\u201cjust\nanything.\u201d\nFrom all classes and ages they\ncame to sign up in this registra\ntion, unprecedented in the history\nof any tig American city. The ma\njority were men, coming mainly\nfrom the laboring and industrial\ngroups, but there were many wo\nmen\u2014mothers, and women with de\npendents.\nEvery age, from an 11 year old\nlad in tattered trousers and torn\nsweater\u2014nothing more to the\nwhite haired 70 year old man of\nsoldierly bearing, who was grad\nuated from Bonn university in Ger\nnrany, was there.\nSeven thousand teachers gave up\ntheir Saturday holiday to help with\nthe work. When they arrived at\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nMother Dashes\nlolleMk^ith\nBaby in Arms\nCries of Chikfr*en Trapped\nin Burning House\nCauses Rash Action\nWANCHESE, N. C., Nov. B'UP>\u2014\nSpurred by the cries of her two\ntrapped children, a mother dashed\nto death in the flames of her burn\ning home, unwittingly carrying a\ntwo months old baby with her.\nThe charred bodies of the four\u2014\nMrs. Ella Barnett, 21, Armeta Bar\nnett, 4; Howard Barnett, 2, and the\nboby, Lottie\u2014were found nestled to\ngether when the flames gave way\nto ashes.\nThe wife of a fisherman who was\naway on a cruise, Mrs. Barnett was\nalone with her children in the\nhome. She awakened to find the\nhouse filled with smoke.\nScreaming, she rushed to a neigh\nbors house carrying the babv and\nsummoned aid. Returning, she ran\ninto the house to get the other chil\ndren with baby Lottie still in her\narms.\nAll died in the flames. The\nwomen of this fishing village, all\ntheir men folk away at sea. stood\nby helplessly.\nReady to Take\nOff On Flight\nDo-X Takes On 2612 Gal\nlons Gasoline in Prep\naration for Trip\nAMSTERDAM. Nov. 8. UP)\u2014The\nGeipian flying boat DO-X took on\n10.000 liters (about 2.642 gallons)\nof motor fuel today in preparation\nfor a probable start toward South\nampton at 9:30 o'clock tomorrow\nmorning.\nFinal decision to hop off on an\nother lap of a projected flight to\nAmerica will be deferred, however,\nuntil weather, reports are studied in\nthe morning.\nAssistant Immigration\nChief Will Hunt Sheep\nOn Papago Reservation\nTUCSON, Artz., Nov. 8. Uh\u2014\nGeorge J. Harris, assistant commis\nsioner general of immigration,\nWashington. D. C., arrived here to\nday en route to the Papago Indian\nreservation southwest of Tucson,\nwhere he will hunt mountain sheep.\nAccompanying Mr. Harris were\nC. M. Smith Washington stafi\nmember of Pictorial*Review; Alden\nJ. Milliken, Immigration inspector\nin charge of the El Paso, Texas, of\nfice, and J. D Milton. pioneer im\nmigration insiiector of Fairbank.\nAnz.\nfiouglas^i ^Hispatch\n-l. L\nTWENTY PAGES TODAY\nEmmet Mc\u00dfride\nFaces Court\n4\nV jT\nMMr\nL\nHerr to Emmet Mc\u00dfride, brother\nof Scott Mc\u00dfride, superintend\nent of the Anti-Salcon League,\nphotographed as he was Uken\nback to Ohio from Washington\nto answer charges of issuing bad\nchecks. Sheriff John P. Kemp\nfome of Carrollton, Ohio, went\nto Washington to get him.\nThreat of Flood\nFaced By London\nAs Thames Rises\nSeine At Paris and Oder\nAt Frankfort Cause\nAlarm and Damage\nLONDQN, Nov. 8 The. slyg\ngish Thames, swollen by persistent\nrains, threatened the low-lying\nsections of London tonight. The\nseine overflowing her banks was\ncausing concern in Paris; the river\nOder was higher at Frankfort than\nat any time since 1854 and\nthroughout central Europe the au\nthorities were vigilant to prevent\nJoss of life and property by me\nhecing floods.\nIwa x junco<, winter of 1929.\nwhen ^Belting snows sent flood\nwaters pouring through France,\nGermany. Belgium and the Balkans\nhas the danger appeared so real\nas now tn the wake of the terrific\ngales which swept England and\nthe continent last week.\nAt high tide today the Thames\nrose to its highest level since the\ndisastrous floods of 1928 and at\nPutney and Rotherhite the river\nover-flowed.\nBasement dwellers were warned\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nAny Forecasts\nOn Enforcement\nReport Guesses\nWickersham Says Com\nmission Has Reached\nNo Conclusion to Print\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 8. Any\nforecasts of what the law enforce\nment commission may recommend\nin its forthcoming report on pro\nhibition were described by Chair\nman Wickersham today as \"purely\nConjectural.\"\nAt the same time he said the\nI commission had reached no con\nclusions which were ready for pub\nlication and that it could not say\nwhen the report will be submitted.\nThe revival of a rumor the com\nmission would recommend modifi\ncation of the prohibition laws to\npermit the sale of 2.75 per cent\nContinued on Page Eight)\nStanley Boynton\nIs At Rochester-\nOn Flight East\nROCHESTER. N. Y.. Nov. 8. uh\u2014\nStanley Boynton. 18-year old Maine\naviator, landed here at 3:57 p. m.\ntoday on the flight in which he\nseeks to get a new west, to east\ntranscontinental record for junior\nfliers. He flew the 350 miles from\nDetroit in one hour and 38 minutes.\nHe said he would spend the night\nhere, leaving for Rockland. Me.,\nabout 10:30 a. m. tomorrow.\n\nSanta Ana Times Sold\nSANTA ANA. Cal.. Nov. 8. oP>\u2014\nAnnouncement was made today of\nthe sale of the Santa Ana Times,\nan afternoon newspaper, to J. Frank\nBurke. own*r of the Santa Ana\nRegister. Today marked the last\npublication of the Tunes. It was\nowned by M. C. and D. E. Maloney\nand had been established two years.\nEmergency\nAction Plan\nOf Hoover\nPresident Will Ask Con\ngress to Rush Appro\npriations for Work\nDrought Sufferers To Be\nGiven Assistance Also\nFurther Intensification of\nPublic Works To Be\n1 Asked\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 8. (API\n\u2014Pi trident Hoever plana to ask\ncongress tor emergency ap\npropriations to furnish employ\nment and ar-ist drought suffer\ners.\nThe one will go toward speed\ning up the government's build\ning program and the other will\ntake the form of a seed loan.\nA statement euciining the\nplan came from the White\nHouse late today after the war\ndepartment and his emergency\nemployment committee had\nseparately made known further\nphases of their own relief pro\ngrams.\nThe statement follows:\nThe president announced the \u2022ad\nministration had decided to recom\nmend to congress a special emerg\nency appropriation to be applied to\nthe further intensification of pub\nlic works, public building and other\nforms of iederal construction which\nare already authorized by congress\nbut for which no appropriations\nwould normally be made until later\nperiods; and further to recommend\nthe provision of a 'seed loan' assist\nant to farmers in the drought area.\n\"It will be remembered the ap\npruprtatlons for federal construction\nwere greatly increased upon the\npresident's recommendation by the\nlast congress as aid to employment\nduring the current year. The de\npartments were also authorized to\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nTampico Police\nJail Communists\nIn Demonstration\nAmerican Consulate Is\nScene of Rioting and\nAttack On U. S. Gov\nernment\nTAMPICO, Mex., Nov. 8 UH\u2014\nThirty-three communists, including\nfour women, were under arrest to\nday as the result of a demonstra\ntion before the American consulate\nlast night.\nThe reds, observing the 13th an\nmversary of the bolshevik revolu\ntions, paraded before the consulate\nand attacked the United States\ngovernnent, Mexican authorities and\nthe press. The names of Sacco and\nVanzetti, whose execution by Mas\nsachusetts authorities in 1927\naroused widespread communist pro\ntests, were shouted frequently.\nPolice also raided the officers of\nthe workers federation of Tamaul\nipas, charging that It #as dominat\ned by communists and other ex\ntremists.\nA-\nGerman Delegate\nMakes Suggestion\nLeague Conference Turns\nDown Proposal to Lim\nit Conscription\nGENEVA, Nov. 8. Uh \u2014Count Von\nBernstorff's proposal to limit the\nnumber of army conscripts called\n|to the colors each year by parties\nIto the League of Nations prepara\ntory disarmament conference was\nrejected by the commission today.\nApproval, however, was voted an\nalternative principle for limitation\n:of the period of conscript service.\nOnly five nations supported the\nGerman recommendation Russia,\nChina. Sweden. Norway and Hol\nland. The United States. Great\nBritain and Canada, while not vot-\ning, were understood to approve the\nproposal in substance although they\nbelieved it useless to attempt to\nforce such limitation on states\nwhich rely upon conscription for\nth?ir military defense forces.\nFrance. Italy. Japan. Poland.\nJugoslavia. Szechoslovakia. Belgium.\nRumania and other states adhering\nto the conscript system, stood sol\nidly against Von Bernstorff\u2019s pro\nposal. The German delegate took\nhis defeat phllosopmcaUy, content\ning himself with reserving Ger\nmany's right to renew Its efforts\ntoward conscript limitation when a\ngeneral conference is called.\n.cDAI LY\nDOUGLAS, ARIZONA. SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 9, 1930.\n'lk -<jKsn\u201d*W.\nJBw W Ibhia\nw .4. zi..,\n\"Calamity Jane,\" thr gun which fired the last 4iot of the World war, otiicial Mme. 10-59-59. November\n11. 1918. This gun is of particular Interest to Douglas pc-'ple. since it was fired by Battery \u201cE,\u201d 11th\nI ield Artillery, which was organised here in Douglas. Formerly the unit was the 308th Cavalry regiment,\nwhose colors are now in the possession of the Fred HUburr. Post of the American Lcgiok. This picture to\nthe property of Wm. Engelke, who is directing the American Legion war spectacle, \"The Spirit of No\nMan s Land,\u201d al the fair grounds on Armistice Day.\nBig Reward Spurs\nSearch for Train\nRobbers On G\u00bbaJ\nSIO,OOO Offered To Be Di\nvided With S2OOO On\nEach of Outlaws\nOAKLAND. Cal., Nov. 8.\nWith a 810,000 reward to spur them\n0n\u201482.000 for each outlaw\u2014peace\nofficers of the San Francisco bay\nregion today spread a net which\nthey hoped would result in capture\nof the five men who yesterday held\nup and robbed a Southern Pacific\nmail car of 855.700 at Nobel station,\n1 a suburb.\nOakland, Berkeley and San Jose\ndetectives and sheriff's deputies,\naided by the state department of\ncriminal identification at Sacra\nmento, brought into play all avail\nable modern scientific equipment to\nrun down the robbers who with the\nflair and bravado of the old west\nand the machine like precision of\nlatter day racketeers, took their\nloot and disappeared within a half\nan hour without injuring Anyone.\nThe large blue sedan used by the\nrobbers was found in Berkeley to\nday near the University of Califor\nnia campus, where, presumably, it\nwas abandoned aurmg the night.\nThe car was covered with dew. It\nwas taken to a garage and dried and\nthree excellent finger prints on it\nwere photographed. These prints\nwere rushed to the state bureau of\ncriminal identification in Sacra\nmento to be checked with records\nxaonun'Kd on Pace Eizht>\nMexican Consulate\nIn Tucson Closes I\nAs Phoenix Opens\nTUCSON, Nov. 8 <JP)\u2014Luis F. l\nCastro, Mexican consul in Tucson,\nwas named consul in Phscnix in\norders received at the consulate\nhere today from Mexico city. I\nRafael Urdaneta, assistant consul\nat Tucson, was named vice cjnsul\nof Phoenix.\nCastro will succeed Manuel Pay-\nno Mariscal, present Phoenix con-\nsul, who is being transferred to a\ngovernment position in Mexico.\nMariscal's assistant, Rosendo Ser-\nna. formerly connected with the\nTucson office, is transferred to'\nLima, Peru.\nThe Tucson consulate, it was 1\nannounced, will be closed. The\nvarious changes are to take effect\nNovember 25.\nFormal Recognition Accorded Brazilian\nRevolutionary Government By Washington\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 8 \u2022*\u00bb\u2014First\nof the major world powers to rec\nognize the new provisional govern\nment of Brazil, the United States\nformally acknowledged today the\nadministration of provisen Presi\ndent Getulio Vargas to be the\ncontrolling political factor in that\ncountry.\nRecognition by the United States\nof the new Brazilian regime was\nannounced by Secretary Stimson\nFired Last Shot O( World War\nWarmer Weather\nMarks Last Week\nFrom Week Before\nThe temperature moved up\nthree degrees last week as com\npired with the week before.\nWith Christmas little more than\nfix weeks away, the present\nweather cannot be regarded\notherwise than as exceptional,\nthe mercury reaching a min\nimum of 70 degrees daily.\nLow High\nSunday 47 76\nManway 57 73\nTuesday 57 78\nWednesday 45 73\nThun day 53 70\nFriday 40 73\nSaturday 40 73\nAverage 48 73\nGeneral average 60\nBritten Predicts\nRepublican Loss\nIf Dry Law Holds\nSays Vole Clearly Denf\nonst rates People Are\nTired of Experiment\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 8 UP)\u2014The\nassertion unless the Volstead act\nwas modified within the next two\nyears President Hoover and the\nrepublican party would meet de\nfeat at the next presidential elec\ntion, was made today by Repre\nsentative Britten, republican. Illi\nnois, an opponent of prohibition.\n\"President Hoover.\u201d the Illinois\nmember said, \"would please the\ncountry at large and do much to\nbring back prosperity to the farm\ners, if he would see to it the.\nWickersham law enforcement com\nmission reported favorably for\nmodification of the Volstead act to\npermit the manufacture and sale\nof beer. He should take a firm\nstand for modification.\"\nBritten said Tuesday's election\nincreased the \"number of wets in\nthe house by 40, clearly indicating\nthe people of the country are tired\nof the prohibition farce that has\nmade beer barons and rum-run\nners wealthy and a menace to the\nnation.\u201d\nThe referenda in Illinois, Rhode\nIsland and Massachusetts, Britten\nsaid, \"clearly demonstrates the peo\nple are tired of this noble ex\nperiment.\u201d\nafter a conference with President\nHoover and upon receiving from\nAmbassador Morgan at Rio Df\nJaneiro a report upon the entire\nqestion of recognition. In addi\ntion, the Brazilian administration\nhad made a formal request for\nsuch action.\nThe recount ion was accorded 15\ndays after the government of for\nmer President Washington Luis\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nArizona Chiefs\nI Confer to Work\nOn Unemployment\nI\nPlan to Send Out Warn\ni ing That Work Is Not\nPlentiful Here\nPHOENIX, Nov. 8 Plans for\nthe relief of the unemployed in Ari\nzona were discussed today at a con\nference called by Governor John C.\nPhillips and attended by Dr. John\nW. Flinn of Prescott, chairman of\nthe state committee on unemploy\nment.\nSuggestions made at the confer\nence will be considered by the state\ncommittee which will be named\nwithin a few days by the governor\nand Dr. Flinn.\nThose offering proposals of relief\nincluded Miss Grace Sparks, of\nPrescott, secretary oi the Yavapai\ncounty chamber of commerce, and\nW. I. Ettleman of Phoenix. Both of\nthem .suggested a survey of the\nstate in which all unemployed would\nbe legtetered and the urging of\neveryone to start construction pro\njects they may have contemplated.\nSeveral made the statement that\nArizona\u2019s greatest problem is the\ntransient unemployed who have\nbeen drawn here on accoutn of Ari\nzona's mild winter climate and the\nerroneous report that work is plen\ntiful in the state.\nThe unemployment committee, it\nwas urged, also should take steps to,\nwarn laborers elsewhere that condi-'\ntions are not good in Arizona.\nGovernor Phillips and Dr. Flinn\nare expected to name a state-wide\ncommittee to consider the entire\nproblem within the next week.\nAfter organization the committee\nwill take definite steps to provide\nmore work both in agricultural and\nindustrial lines as well as in build\ning.\n\nLumber Schooner\nTurns Over; Sinks\nCrew of Seventeen Men\nBelieved to Have Per\nished in Harbor\nEUREKA, Calif., Nov. 8 UP)\u2014The\ncoast guard life saving station\nhere reported tonight the steam\nlumber schooner Brooklyn turned\nover and sank while crossing Hum\nboldt bar at the entrance of the\nharbor late today. It was be\nlieved the 17 men of her crew were\nall drowned.\nThe water was extremely rough\nover the bar. the coast guard said,\nand apparently the lumber schoon\ner was struck by a large wave and\nturned over. The coast guard sent\nboats to look for bodies of the\nmen.\nThe Brooklyn is owned by the\nBayside Steamship company of\nSan Francisco and Eureka and car\nries lumber between those ports.\nCapt. T. Tuszesson, San Francisco,\nwas scipper of the craft.\nThe Brooklyn was hit simultan\neously by two mountainous waves,\nthe coast guard said, blew her\nwhistle and within five minutes 1\nhad sunk.\nJorgen* M. Greeve was chief of\nficer aboard the Brooklyn; F. V. J\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nTWENTY PAGES TOD.\nControl Looms\nAs Big Issue\nIn Both Camps\nDry Agents Nab\nSheriff Among\nSeven Arrested\nCharged With Conspiracy\nto Violate the National\nDry Laws\nMONTGOMERY, Ala., Nov. 8\n\u2014Federal prohibition agents early\ntoday arrested seven persons, in\ncluding, they said, the sheriff and\nsheriff-elect of Lowndes county at\nHaynesville. They are charged with\nconspiracy to violate the national\nprohibition act.\nThe seven men were brought here\nand bonds for all except two negroes\ncaught in the raids were set at\n$15,000. For the negroes who were\ncharged with possession wau set at\nSSOO.\nThe officers said those arrested\nwere. Sheriff Morrow Willoughby,\nBuck Meadows, sheriff-elect; Leon\nWest, a deputy sheriff, H. N. Pat\nterson and Wilbur Winn, all of\nHaynesville.\nJames W. Shields of New Orleans,\nfederal prohibition agent, who said\nhe had spent 30 days in Lowndes\ncuunty gathering evidence, said he\nled the raiding party.\nShields, according to United\nStates District Attorney Grady\nReynolds here reported he had made\npurc\u2019,as<j of liquor direct from\nSheriff Willoughby while posing as\na racketeer from St. Louis and last\nnight set a trap for the officer.\nShields said he arranged for a\nmeeting at a negro shack in Hay\nnesville and Deputy West appeared 1\nand a deal was closed for deliver^ of\n40 gallons. Shields said when ar-'\nrested a short time later, West had[\nin his possession S2OO in marked\nbills passed in completing the deal.\nBoth Meadows and Willoughby\nwho made bond, denied any con-'\nspiracy existed and each declared'\nhe was at home asleep when officers.\ncame to arrest him.\nEdwards Is Freed\nIn Murder Trial\nIn Tucson Court\nCharge of Slaying Negro\nGardener Before Jury\nThree Hours\nTUCSON, Nov. 8 Uh\u2014A. jury in\nsuperior court here tonight acquitted\nArthur D. Edwards, Tucson con\ntractor, who was charged with first\ndegree murder in connection with\nthe slaying last July of Fred Wash\nington, negro gardener. Hie jury\ndeliberated three hours.\nEdwards claimed he shot to death\nthe negro in self defense. Testifying\nin his own behalf today, he said\nWashington ran amuck during a\nquarrel over fifty cents alleged to\nhave been owed him by F. D. Ham\nilton, a friend of the accused man,\nat whose home the shooting oc\ncured.\nBoth Edwards and Hamilton, a\nwitness for the state, testified the\nquarrel and slaying of the gardener\nfollowed several hours spent by\nthem in drinking.\nTrial Judge Fred W. Fickett\ncharged the jury it might return\none of four verdicts, acquittal or\nguilt or either first or second de\ngree murder or of manslaughter.\nPrisoner of Cave-In\nIs Rescued When Calls\nAre Heard By Workers\nSANTA MONICA, Calif.. Nov. 8\n\u2014From within the dirt walls of a\ncave-in that threatened to en\ntomb him, G. W. Hiram, 22-year\nold laborer, shouted directions to\nday to fellow workers, enabeling\nthem to rescue him.\nHiram was imprisoned when a\nwall of a pit he and others were\ndigging collapsed.\nHe was taken out suffering a\nbroken arm and probable internal\ninjuries.\nClemens to Fair Commission\nPHOENIX, Ariz., Nov. 8.\nGovernor John C. Phillips an\nnounced the appointment today of\nMark Twain Clemens, of Florence,\nas a member of the state fair com\nmission.\nThe Florence man fills the vac\nancy on the commission created\nseveral weeks ago when P. D. Over\nfield resigned to accept the secre\ntaryship of the fair. 'I\nMetal Market\nCopper quiet; electrolytic, spot and\nuture 9%. Iron quiet; unchanged.\nTin easy; spot and nearby 25.62;\n.\u2019uture 25.90. Lead steady; spot N.\nSf, 5.10; East St. Louis 4.95. Zinc\nH j ?t; East St. Louis spot and fu-\nM c 4.40-4.45. Antimony 7.12. Bar\ns 36\u00bbkc.\nNumber 114\nFinal, But Unofficia\nCount, Gives Republi\ncans Majority of One\nScore Of Contested\nHouse Elections }Up\nEighth Indiana District\nPresents Most Interest\ning Situation\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 8 (AP)\n\u2014Ucrted in seeking a return\nof prosperity, national party\nleaders returned to the busi\nness today of trying to find\nout who won eongresMonal con\ntrol in Tuesday's biennial elec\ntion.\nRepublicans and democrats\nboth were determined to fight\nH out to the last vote in the\nlast precincts and it was ob\nvious tonight the actual con\ntrolling party of the next sen\nate and house probably will not\nbe determined until the close-\n(Continued on Page Eight\nRains and Fogs\nTie Up Aviation I\nAt Paris Field\nTwo French Aviation Venl\ntures Cause Worry A|\nPlanes Not Reported\nLE BOURGET, France, Nov. B^l\n\u2014Execrable flying weather, accoml\npanted by rains and fogs, raise!\nhavoc with passenger air service al\nthis field today and caused worrl\nfor two French aviation venture!\nMlle. Lena Bernstein, Franco!\nRussian aviatrix, took off at K\no\u2019clock for a flight to Tokyo an!\nwau scheduled to reach Marseilles fl\n2:30 o\u2019clock this afternoon. She ha!\nnot arrived at 7:40 p. m., nor ha!\nanything been heard from her. g\nAnxiety also was felt for tM\nsafety of Captain Goulette arfl\nPilot Jean LaLouiette, who left hefl\nat 1:20 a. m. in an attempt fl\nbreak the ten-day airmaij recofl\nbetween Paris and Saigon, Incifl\nChina. Their first scheduled lanfl\ning was at Athens, where they wefl\ndue at 3 p. m., but they had nfl\nreached the Grecian capital at 7 I\nm.\nLaLouette sprang into fame lafl\nsummer when he piloted Carfl\nCaraiman to Rumania in the aerifl\ncoup d\u2019etat that made the exilfl\ncrown prince a king.\nSocialists Mourn\nGerman Monarch\nLeaders Will Gather i\nCitizen\u2019s 'Beer Cells\nfor Observance\nMUNICH, Germany, Nov. 8 vF\nIn the same \u201ccitizens beer cells\nwhere Adolph Hitler hatched 1\nabortive plans for an overthrow\nthe government in 1823, the natiox\nsocialists will gather tomorrow\nmourning services to commemon\nthe twelfth anniversary of the G\nman revolution which establish\nthe republic.\nOriginally it was planned for\nband of \u201cbrown shirts\u201d to mai\nthrough the city, as Hitler 1\nhoped to march with Ludendo\nseven years ago, and to hold servi\nat the cemetery where lie those a\nfell in the revolution of 1928. I\nthe police forbade such a derm\nstration and the Hitler follow\nI turned to the storied old beer cel\nAdvertisements of tomorro\nmeeting have not indicated whet\nHitler himself is to speak, menti<\ning only Alfred Wagner, a mem\nof the Bavarian diet as the di\norator.\n\nEngineer Is Arrested\nIn Bank Robbery That\nTook Place In Augi\nSAN FRANCISCO, Nov. 8. U\nPolice today arrested Sam D. Ruel\n30, civil engineer of Burlingame,\nconnection with a bank holdup\nLos Angeles last August. Rud\nthe police said, confessed.\nRucker, detectives said, entc\nthe bank waving a package he I\nwas dynamite. The teller gave 1\n$1,200 and he fled.\nLos Angeles police were 1\nafter the suspect today.","height":"26589","width":"20604"}}
